The write-down of European debt is inevitable.
Berkeley – – "That was just the Greek crisis," or "That was just the Greek and Irish crisis," people used to think. But not anymore, because it is clearly an eurozone crisis.
To address it is both easier and harder than usually anticipated.
The economics of this crisis are quite simple.
Greece's finances are problematic.
The banking sector in Ireland has issues.
The private bond market in Portugal has issues.
Spain has problems in all three areas.
While the details differ, the conclusion is the same: these countries will all have to undergo painful austerity processes.
To offset the side effects of austerity policies, the usual approach is to combine domestic cuts with domestic currency devaluation.
Devaluation enhances export competitiveness, essentially using external demand to supplement internal demand.
However, these countries are all part of the Eurozone and do not have their own independent currencies to devalue. Therefore, they can only substitute external devaluation with internal devaluation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to enhance export competitiveness, thereby increasing external demand.
In fact, the determination of these crisis-hit countries to tighten their belts is considerable.
But one economic variable has not changed alongside the adjustment of other variables: the debt levels of both the public and private sectors.
<s>Government's book value of accumulated debt has not changed, and bank debts – except for some owed to ordinary creditors (junior creditors) – have remained largely unchanged.
<s>This simple fact puts the internal devaluation strategy in a self-contradictory situation: the more wages and other costs are cut, the heavier the relative burden of accumulated debt becomes.
<s>The heavier the debt burden, the more public spending needs to be reduced and taxes increased to service the government’s and its defenders’ (such as banks) debts.
<s>This, in turn, requires further internal devaluation, pushing up the debt burden even more, leading to a vicious cycle that drags the economy into depression.
<s>Therefore, to make the internal devaluation strategy work, ways must be found to reduce the face value of debt.
Government debt must be restructured.
Bank debt must be converted into equity, and bank liabilities should be written off when they exceed assets.
Mortgage debt also needs to be reduced.
Policymakers are unwilling to go down this road, and that is understandable.
The sanctity of contracts must be upheld.
Government is concerned about losing credibility in financial markets.
If creditors are mainly foreign, especially foreign banks, haircuts would only drag down other countries.
These concerns cannot be dismissed, but they should not lead to unreasonable conclusions.
The solutions are only two: internal devaluation or external devaluation.
European leaders must choose one of these two options.
The external devaluation option was unanimously excluded.
But internal devaluation inevitably requires debt restructuring.
To deny this is both unreasoned and illogical.
The operation of debt restructuring is straightforward.
The government can issue a batch of claims, with face values discounted at a certain ratio compared to existing debt face values.
#1 <s>Bondholders can choose either to hold their bonds to maturity at par value but with a longer maturity and lower interest rates, or to accept a discount bond with a lower face value than their existing bonds but with an earlier maturity and higher interest rates.
#2 <s>This is not cutting-edge technology; people have attempted it before.
#3 <s>But for it to succeed, there are three prerequisites.
#4 <s>The first is to assure bondholders of the safety of the new bonds.
#5 <s>Someone needs to come forward to guarantee this batch of bonds.
During the 1980s, when the Brady Plan was implemented for Latin American debt restructuring, the United States Treasury played the role of the "guarantor big brother."
Now, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, countries must act in concert.
Otherwise, the restructuring of one country would raise expectations for others, leading to contagion.
Finally, banks that suffer losses from debt restructuring need to have their balance sheets strengthened.
These banks need to undergo genuine stress tests, not the perfunctory ones conducted earlier this year.
If debt restructuring signals capital shortfalls, then comprehensive equity-for-debt swaps must be carried out for the affected banks.
If that is not enough, then governments must inject capital into the relevant banks.
This too needs to be done in concert across countries.
Once bank balance sheets are strengthened, it may be possible to restructure mortgage, bank, and other private sector debts without destabilizing the entire financial system.
Now let's talk about the biggest challenge.
All of this requires firm leadership.
German leaders must recognize that German banks have significant exposure to debt in eurozone peripheral countries, and the situation is dire.
They must convince backroom bosses and voters that using public funds to guarantee debt reprofiling and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for internal devaluation strategies; since Germany is encouraging other EU countries to adopt such strategies, it should shoulder its responsibility as guarantor.
In short, European leaders, particularly those in Germany, need to make the consequences sound more serious – or else the consequences will be dire.
Because that is the facts.
